# KB document format ↔ markdown chunker contract

Two artifacts share an implicit contract:

- **Producer:** `EXTRACTION_SYSTEM_PROMPT` (`packages/kb-tool/src/prompts/extraction.ts`) — an LLM system prompt that turns raw anonymized docs (support emails, transcripts, articles) into structured markdown for the KB. Output always has a heading hierarchy (`#` title, `**Topics:**`/`**Date:**` metadata lines, then `##`/`###` sections), but heading **names are not fixed** and change as the prompt evolves.
- **Consumer:** the header-aware markdown chunker (`packages/sandbox/src/markdownChunker.ts`, `chunkMarkdown()`) — splits that markdown into chunks for embedding/retrieval by walking heading **structure**, never heading names.

Breaking this contract throws no error. It silently degrades retrieval.

## 1. The structural contract

The chunker splits along **heading structure, not heading names**. It:

- Parses the document into a tree of sections by markdown ATX heading level (`#`, `##`, `###`, …).
- Chunks at the level of **leaf sections** (deepest headings): a section with sub-headings recurses into them; a section with none becomes a chunk itself.
- Optionally prepends a **breadcrumb** (document title + ancestor headings) to each chunk's *embedded* text only — never its stored/displayed text.
- Reuses the paragraph chunker (`chunkText` in `chunker.ts`) as a **fallback** to split any single leaf section exceeding the ~800-token target. This mirrors how `emailThreadChunker.ts` already wraps `chunkText`.
- Treats content **before the first heading** (the `# title` line plus `**Topics:**` / `**Date:**` metadata lines) as document metadata, **not** a content chunk.

This **generalizes the existing `emailThreadChunker.ts` pattern** (H3 splitting via `splitByH3` + `chunkText` fallback for oversized sections + greedy packing to ~800 tokens + `mergeTinyTrailingChunks`) to **arbitrary heading depth**. Read `packages/sandbox/src/emailThreadChunker.ts` as the reference implementation for style and shape.

## 2. Invariants to preserve when editing the extraction prompt

You MAY:

- Rename headings, add/remove topical sections, change wording and instructions.

You MUST:

- Keep output as well-formed markdown with a clear heading hierarchy.
- **Make each independently retrievable unit of knowledge its own leaf section under a heading** — the single most important property. For Q&A content: one heading per question. For articles: one heading per topic.

You MUST NOT:

- Flatten everything into one big section with no sub-headings (the whole doc collapses into one oversized chunk).
- Bury distinct questions/topics as inline paragraphs under a single shared heading (they stop being independently retrievable).

You SHOULD:

- Keep a self-contained summary-style section (whatever it is named) — a high-recall standalone chunk that often matches user queries better than the detailed phrasing underneath.
- Keep any metadata lines before the first heading in `**Key:** value` shape, each on its own line (topics, date are extracted into chunk metadata).

> Heading names like a "summary", "question", or "details" section are **illustrative only** — never required strings. The contract is about structure, not labels.

## 3. Why this matters

RAG retrieval quality depends on each chunk being one self-contained idea. The prompt does the structuring; the chunker trusts that structure. Breaking the contract raises no error — it silently degrades answer quality, which is hard to debug later.

## 4. Cross-references

- Extraction prompt: `packages/kb-tool/src/prompts/extraction.ts` (`EXTRACTION_SYSTEM_PROMPT`). *(present in this checkout)*
- Markdown chunker: `packages/sandbox/src/markdownChunker.ts` (`chunkMarkdown()`). *(present in this checkout)*
- Reference implementation: `packages/sandbox/src/emailThreadChunker.ts`.
- Paragraph fallback chunker: `packages/sandbox/src/chunker.ts` (`chunkText`).

A change to the extraction prompt should prompt a review of the chunker, and vice versa.
